Which type contributed the most shows on Netflix?

In [ ]:
#GroupBy Type
df_type = df.groupby(by = 'type').agg(count = ('type','count')).reset_index()

#Identify highest values
most_type = df_type[df_type['count'] == df_type['count'].max()]['type'].values[0]
most_type_value = df_type[df_type['count'] == df_type['count'].max()]['count'].values[0]
most_type_pct = (most_type_value / df_type.sum()[1]) * 100

#Plot chart
sns.barplot(data=df_type, x='type', y='count')
plt.xlabel('Type')
plt.ylabel('No. of shows')
plt.title('No. of shows by types')
plt.show()

#Comment
print(f'Most of the shows on Netflix are {most_type} with {most_type_value} shows, contains about {most_type_pct:.2f}% overall.')

Most of the shows on Netflix are Movie with 6126 shows, contains about 69.69% overall.

#Filter 2 specific dataframe to see the duration of each
df_movie = df[df['type']=='Movie']
df_tvshow = df[df['type']=='TV Show']

#Convert dtype
df_movie['duration'] = df_movie['duration'].str.replace(' min', '')
df_movie['duration'] = df_movie['duration'].astype(int)

df_tvshow['duration'] = df_tvshow['duration'].str.replace(' Seasons', '').str.replace(' Season', '')
df_tvshow['duration'] = df_tvshow['duration'].astype(int)

#GroupBy duration
df_movie_duration = df_movie.groupby(by = 'duration').agg(count = ('duration','count')).reset_index()
df_tvshow_duration = df_tvshow.groupby(by = 'duration').agg(count = ('duration','count')).reset_index()

Which rating are popular on Netflix?

Here are the meanings of some of the abbreviations used in the context of age ratings and classifications for movies and TV shows:

  1. TV-MA: This rating is for TV programs intended for mature audiences, typically aged 17 and older.
  2. TV-14: This rating is for TV programs intended for viewers aged 14 and older, and they may contain content unsuitable for viewers under 14.
  3. TV-PG: This is a rating for family-friendly TV programs, though there may be some content unsuitable for young children.
  4. R: This rating is for movies suitable for viewers aged 17 and older, or they may contain content unsuitable for viewers under 17.
  5. PG-13: This rating is for movies suitable for viewers aged 13 and older, or it may require adult guidance.
  6. TV-Y7: TV programs for viewers aged 7 and older.
  7. TV-Y: This rating is for TV programs suitable for all audiences, including children.
  8. PG: This is a rating for family-friendly movies, although there may be some content unsuitable for young children.
  9. TV-G: This is a rating for family-friendly TV programs, suitable for all audiences.
  10. NR: "Not Rated," typically used for works that haven't gone through an official rating process.
  11. G: This rating is for family-friendly movies, suitable for all audiences.
  12. TV-Y7-FV: TV programs for viewers aged 7 and older, but they may contain more parental guidance.
  13. NC-17: This rating is for movies suitable for viewers aged 17 and older, and it's stricter than an R rating.
  14. UR: "Unrated," often used when a work has not been rated or to indicate uncertainty about the suitability for a specific audience.

Which is the "boom" year of Netflix?

In [ ]:
#GroupBy added_year
df_year = df.groupby(by = 'added_year').agg(counting = ('added_year','count')).reset_index().sort_values(by = 'added_year',ascending=True)

#Identify max/min count
max_count = max(df_year["counting"])
min_count = min(df_year["counting"])
max_year = df_year["added_year"][df_year["counting"].idxmax()]
min_year = df_year["added_year"][df_year["counting"].idxmin()]

#Plot chart
sns.lineplot(data = df_year
             ,x = 'added_year'
             ,y = 'counting')
plt.scatter(max_year, max_count, color='red', zorder=5)
plt.scatter(min_year, min_count, color='red', zorder=5, marker= 'o')
plt.text(max_year - 0.3, max_count + 50, f'Max = {max_count}', ha='right')
plt.text(min_year, min_count + 50, f'Min = {min_count}', ha='right')

plt.axvline(x=max_year, color='gray', linestyle='--', label=f'Max Year ({max_year})')

plt.xticks(df_year["added_year"])
plt.ylim(0,2500)
plt.xlabel("Added Year")
plt.ylabel("No. of shows")
plt.title("No. of shows by Year")
plt.xticks(rotation=45)

plt.show()

#Comment
print(\
f'It can be clearly seen that the No. of shows witness the lowest value at {min_count} in {min_year}.\n\
This number dramatically multiplied {max_count/min_count:.0f} times by the end of {max_year}.\n\
\n\
In 2019, due to the effect of COVID-19 epidemic, with people in many parts of the world restricted from leaving\n\
their homes and social activities, many users have increased their demand for online entertainment services. \n\
Netflix has benefited from this increase in demand for online movies and home entertainment.'
)

It can be clearly seen that the No. of shows witness the lowest value at 1 in 2010.
This number dramatically multiplied 2016 times by the end of 2019.

In 2019, due to the effect of COVID-19 epidemic, with people in many parts of the world restricted from leaving
their homes and social activities, many users have increased their demand for online entertainment services. 
Netflix has benefited from this increase in demand for online movies and home entertainment.

What are the top 10 categories having highest number of shows?

#stacked listed_in
listed_in = df['listed_in'].str.split(pat = ', ',expand=True).apply(pd.Series).stack().reset_index(drop=True)
listed_in.name = 'category'

#top 10 categories
df_category = pd.DataFrame({'category': listed_in})
df_category_grpby = df_category.groupby(by = 'category').agg(count = ('category','count')).reset_index().sort_values(by = 'count',ascending=False).reset_index(drop=True)
df_top10_category = df_category_grpby.head(10)

#Plot chart
sns.barplot(data= df_top10_category
            ,y = 'category'
            ,x = 'count')

plt.xlabel('No. of Shows')
plt.ylabel('Category')
plt.title('Top 10 categories by No. of Shows')
plt.show()

#Comment
print(\
'Netflix offers a diverse range of content categories, including International Movies, Dramas, Comedies, International TV shows, Documentaries, and more.\n\
This diversity caters to a wide audience with varying preferences.\n\
\n\
Netflix can use these data about categories to enhance its recommendation algorithms. Users who enjoy content in one category may receive recommendations\n\
from related categories, increasing user engagement.\n\
\n\
Moreover, Netflix can use this data for comparative analysis with other streaming platforms to make users understand how its content library compares in\n\
terms of category distribution.\n\
'
)

#Identify top 10 directors
df_director = df.groupby(by = 'director').agg(count = ('director','count')).reset_index().sort_values(by = 'count',ascending=False)
df_top10_director = df_director[df_director['director']!='Unknown'].reset_index(drop = True).head(10)

#Plot chart
sns.barplot(data= df_top10_director
            ,y = 'director'
            ,x = 'count')

plt.xlabel('No. of Shows')
plt.ylabel('Director')
plt.title('Top 10 directors by No. of Shows')
plt.show()

#Top 5 director name
director_name = ", ".join(director_name for director_name in df_top10_director['director'].head(5))
df_top10_director['count_text'] = df_top10_director['count'].astype(str)
director_value = ", ".join(director_value for director_value in df_top10_director['count_text'].head(5))

#Comment
print(f'We can see that there were 5 directors who contributed the highest number of shows.\n\
They are {director_name} with the number of shows are {director_value}, respectively.')

We can see that there were 5 directors who contributed the highest number of shows.
They are Rajiv Chilaka, Raúl Campos, Jan Suter, Marcus Raboy, Suhas Kadav, Jay Karas with the number of shows are 19, 18, 16, 16, 14, respectively.

#Plot map
shapemap = gpd.datasets.get_path('naturalearth_lowres')
world = gpd.read_file(shapemap)
merged = world.set_index('name').join(pd.DataFrame(df_country).set_index('country'))

fig, ax = plt.subplots(1, 1, figsize=(10, 8))
merged.plot(column='count'
            , cmap='Reds'
            , linewidth=0.5
            , ax=ax
            , edgecolor='0.7'
            , legend=True
            , legend_kwds={'orientation': "horizontal"
                           , 'shrink': 0.7
                           }
